\preprint{KEK-TH/1581, KIAS-P/12067}
%\title{Determination of neutrino mass hierarchy with intermediate baseline reactor experiments}
\title{Determination of mass hierarchy with medium baseline reactor
 neutrino experiments}

\author[add1]{Shao-Feng Ge\fnref{Shao-Feng}}
\author[add2,add5]{Kaoru Hagiwara\fnref{Kaoru}}
\author[add3]{Naotoshi Okamura\fnref{Naotoshi}}
\author[add4,add5]{Yoshitaro Takaesu\fnref{Yoshitaro}}
\fntext[Shao-Feng]{gesf02@gmail.com}
\fntext[Kaoru]{kaoru.hagiwara@kek.jp}
\fntext[Naotoshi]{nokamura@yamanashi.ac.jp}
\fntext[Yoshitaro]{takaesu@kias.re.kr}

\address[add1]{KEK Theory Center, Tsukuba, 305-0801, Japan}
\address[add2]{KEK Theory Center and Sokendai, Tsukuba, 305-0801, Japan}
\address[add3]{Faculty of Engineering, University of Yamanashi, Kofu,
 Yamanashi, 400-8511, Japan}
\address[add4]{Department of Physics and Astronomy, Seoul National
 University, Seoul 151-742, Korea}
\address[add5]{School of Physics, KIAS, Seoul 130-722, Korea}

\begin{abstract}
We study the sensitivity of future medium baseline
reactor antineutrino experiments on the neutrino mass hierarchy. By using
 the standard $\chi^2$ analysis, we find that the sensitivity
depends strongly on the baseline length $L$ and the energy resolution $\left(\delta E/E\right)^2 =
\left(a/\sqrt{E/MeV}\right)^2 + b^2$, where $a$ and $b$ parameterize the statistical
 and systematic uncertainties, respectively. The optimal length is found to be $L \sim
 40-55$ km, the larger resolution the shorter optimal $L$.  The running time
 needed to determine the mass hierarchy 
depends strongly on the energy resolution. The 3$\sigma$ determination is 
possible after 10 years of running with $a=3\%$ and $b=0.5\%$, 
which can be reduced to 4 years if $a=2\%$ and $b=0.5\%$, for a 5 kton
 detector (with 12\% weight fraction of free proton) placed at $L \sim 50$ km away
 from a $20 \,{\rm GW_{th}}$ reactor. This type of experiment can measure the relevant
 mixing parameters accurately, achieving
$\delta \sin^22\theta_{12} \sim 4\times 10^{-3}, \delta (m_2^2-m_1^2) \sim 0.03\times 10^{-5} {\rm eV^2},$ and
$\delta |m_3^2 -m_1^2| \sim 0.007\times 10^{-3} {\rm eV^2}$, after 5 years.

% * $\Delta \chi^2$ vs. L distribution with large $\theta_{13}$ determined by
%  Daya Bay and RENO experiments. \\

% * After $25 kT*year$ exposure, the mass hierarchy could be determined with the significance of more
%  than $4\sigma$ using the far detector at 50 km from the reactors if the
%  $1.5\%$ level of energy resolution will be achieved.

% * neutrino mixing parameters, $\sin^2 2\theta_{12}, \Delta m^2_{21}$ and
%  $\Delta m^2_{31}$ could be measured with their uncertainties reduced to
%  around $20\%$ of the current uncertainties after $25kT*year$ run with a $20
%  GW_{th}$ reactor complex. \\

% (* To determine the mass hierarchy, we have to distinguish the difference
%  between the two hierarchies in both the lower and the higher energy region.)

% (* The mass hierarchy cannot be determined with $6\%$ or worse energy
%  resolution.)\\


\end{abstract}

